8:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"StarkNet's early-stage infrastructure introduces technical risks including potential network congestion during high-volume periods and smart contract vulnerabilities. Paradex's limited liquidity compared to major CEXs creates higher slippage risks when unwinding large arbitrage positions quickly. The platform's institutional focus means retail traders may face challenges with minimum position sizes and sophisticated margin requirements. ENA's relatively high correlation with ETH during market stress can reduce the effectiveness of traditional delta-hedging strategies, requiring more sophisticated risk management approaches."}]]}]
9:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Paradex's 1-hour funding cycle affect ENA arbitrage strategies?","answer":"The 1-hour funding cycle allows for more frequent capture of funding rate premiums compared to 8-hour cycles on most exchanges. This higher frequency enables traders to react faster to ENA governance events and protocol announcements that drive funding rate spikes. However, it also requires more active position management and increases transaction costs relative to the funding received."},{"question":"What are the advantages of trading ENA perpetuals on a StarkNet-based DEX?","answer":"StarkNet's validity proof system ensures transaction finality and reduces counterparty risk compared to traditional DEXs. Self-custodial trading eliminates exchange custody risks while maintaining access to sophisticated perpetual futures mechanics. The platform's institutional-grade infrastructure provides better execution quality than many decentralized alternatives."},{"question":"How does ENA's connection to Ethena Protocol affect funding rates?","answer":"Ethena Protocol governance events and USDe backing ratio changes create periodic demand imbalances that significantly impact funding rates. Protocol updates or changes to the delta-hedging strategy can cause sustained periods of positive or negative funding as traders position for governance outcomes. This creates predictable opportunities around known governance events and protocol milestones."},{"question":"What capital requirements are needed for effective ENA funding rate arbitrage on Paradex?","answer":"Effective arbitrage typically requires $50,000+ to overcome the platform's institutional focus and achieve meaningful returns after transaction costs. Portfolio margin requirements demand sufficient collateral to maintain positions across multiple venues during volatile periods. The platform's 0.02%/0.05% fee structure means smaller positions may not generate sufficient funding rate alpha to justify the operational complexity."}]}]
